---
scope: src/service/scaffold/renderArtifact/
description: Rendering pipeline for scaffold artifact pages (commands, agents, skills) with citation metadata sourced from upstream canonical history in versions.json.
intent: >
  Transform each scaffold artifact source file (command, agent, or skill
  shipped by the MCP server during aide_upgrade) into a rendered HTML page
  with citation metadata — publication date, source-commit SHA, stable
  versioned URL — derived exclusively from `.aide/versions.json`, the
  upstream canonical repo's commit history baked into a local file at
  upgrade time. The local repo is a display layer that renders synced
  copies; the canonical repo is the authority for version history and
  citation dates. A reader citing an artifact page must be able to trust
  that the displayed publication date reflects when the artifact was
  authored or revised upstream, not when it was synced into this repo.
outcomes:
  desired:
    - "Every rendered artifact page receives citation metadata where `publishedAt`, `sourceCommit`, and previous-version URL are derived from the `versions.json` entry keyed by the artifact's category-prefixed path — not from local git history, filesystem mtime, or any other source that tracks sync operations rather than upstream authorship."
    - "The key lookup maps the artifact's kind and slug to the correct `versions.json` key using the category prefix convention (`commands/`, `agents/`, `skills/`) matching the file's location relative to `.claude/`."
    - "The build fails loudly with the artifact key name and a diagnostic message if `versions.json` is missing or contains no entry for the artifact being rendered — a missing entry means `aide_upgrade` was not run or the artifact is untracked upstream, and both are build-blocking errors."
    - The markdown rendering pipeline reuses the same strict renderer the docs service uses, applying the same fixed plugin set with no artifact-specific extensions or content injection.
    - The pipeline runs at build time only — no runtime fetch, no network call, no external dependency beyond the local filesystem.
  undesired:
    - "Local git history (`git log`, `git blame`) used as the source for citation dates or commit SHAs. Local commits track `aide_upgrade` sync operations, not artifact authorship — using them produces publication dates that reset to the sync date every time `aide_upgrade` runs, making it impossible to establish when the artifact was originally published or last revised upstream."
    - A silent fallback when versions.json is missing or lacks an entry — rendering the page with empty or placeholder citation metadata, or falling back to local git history as a best effort. The fallback masks a broken upgrade pipeline and ships misleading citation data.
    - A key-mapping scheme that diverges from the convention used by the sibling docs rendering service. Both services consume the same versions.json file; if the key derivation logic differs between them, one will silently fail to find entries the other resolves correctly.
    - "Runtime reads or network calls for citation metadata. The `versions.json` file is a local artifact shipped by the MCP; the build must work fully offline."
---

## Context

This module is the scaffold counterpart to `src/service/docs/renderCanonical/`.
Both services render content shipped by the MCP server during `aide_upgrade` and
both derive citation metadata from the same `.aide/versions.json` file — upstream
canonical repo commit history baked into a local artifact at upgrade time. The
docs service renders canonical methodology documentation (`.aide/docs/*.md`); this
service renders the three scaffold artifact types — commands, agents, and skills —
that `aide_init` installs into a project's `.claude/` directory.

The bug that drove this spec: `extractArtifactCitationMeta` used `git log` against
the local source file to derive `publishedAt` and `sourceCommit`. Local git history
only records when `aide_upgrade` synced the file, not when the artifact was authored
or revised upstream. The result: every artifact page displayed the sync date as the
publication date, and every `aide_upgrade` run reset all citation dates — destroying
the publication history the citation metadata exists to preserve.

## Strategy

**Read `.aide/versions.json` at build time using the same pattern as the docs
service.** The file is a flat object keyed by category-prefixed path. Each entry
contains `publishedAt` (ISO 8601 timestamp), `sourceCommit` (short SHA), and
optionally `previousCommit` (short SHA of the prior version). The key for a given
artifact is derived from its kind and slug using the category prefix convention:

| Kind | Slug | versions.json key |
|------|------|-------------------|
| `command` | `aide-init` | `commands/aide/init` |
| `agent` | `aide-architect` | `agents/aide/aide-architect` |
| `skill` | `study-playbook` | `skills/study-playbook` |

The key derivation must follow the same structural convention the MCP server uses
when generating the file — category prefix matching the `.claude/` subdirectory
structure, not an arbitrary mapping.

**Fail loudly on missing file or missing entry.** If `.aide/versions.json` does not
exist, the build fails with a message naming the file path and advising to run
`aide_upgrade`. If the file exists but contains no entry for the artifact's key, the
build fails naming the key and the artifact kind/slug. There is no fallback to `git
log`, no fallback to empty metadata, no graceful degradation. A missing entry is a
build-blocking error.

**Reuse the same `renderMarkdown` from the docs service.** The artifact source files
are markdown with the same fixed plugin set (GFM tables, fenced code, inline code,
headings, lists, links, emphasis, frontmatter extraction). No artifact-specific
rendering extensions.

## Good examples

A reader visits the "aide init" command page. The citation header shows:

> **Published** 2026-04-12T15:15:14-07:00 · **Source commit** `a9e55a4`

These values match the `commands/aide/init` entry in `.aide/versions.json` exactly.
They reflect when the command was authored and last revised in the upstream canonical
repo, not when the file was synced into this project. A week later, `aide_upgrade`
runs and syncs newer versions of other files but doesn't touch the init command. The
init page still shows the same publication date — it hasn't been revised, so the
date doesn't change.

A reader visits the "aide-architect" agent page. The citation header shows the
`publishedAt` and `sourceCommit` from the `agents/aide/aide-architect` entry in
versions.json. The values are different from the local git log of the file at
`.claude/agents/aide/aide-architect.md` because the local commit reflects the
`aide_upgrade` sync, not the upstream authorship.

## Bad examples

The "aide init" page displays `sourceCommit: 1a06691` and
`published: 2026-04-12T15:46:06-07:00` — values from local `git log`. The versions.json
entry for `commands/aide/init` shows `sourceCommit: a9e55a4` and
`publishedAt: 2026-04-12T15:15:14-07:00`. The page displays the wrong commit and the
wrong date because `extractArtifactCitationMeta` shells out to `git log` instead of
reading versions.json.

Every time `aide_upgrade` runs, ALL artifact pages' publication dates reset to the sync
timestamp. A command that hasn't been revised in a month suddenly shows "Published today."
The citation history is destroyed on every upgrade.

`versions.json` is missing because the developer hasn't run `aide_upgrade` yet. Instead
of failing the build, the page silently renders with today's date and an empty commit SHA.
The developer doesn't notice, the page ships with fabricated citation metadata, and a
reader citing the page gets a date that reflects the build machine's clock, not the
artifact's authorship history.

## References

- `src/service/docs/renderCanonical/.aide` — sibling spec governing the docs rendering
  service, which already reads from `.aide/versions.json` correctly. The same antipattern
  (local git ≠ upstream authorship) and the same fix pattern (read versions.json, fail
  loudly) apply to this module.
- `.aide/versions.json` — the upstream canonical version history file shipped by the MCP
  server. Contains entries for all delivered files keyed by category-prefixed path.
